<section class="mag90" id="first-90-days" aria-label="First 90 Days in Canada">
  <h2>First 90 Days in Canada: A Newcomer Checklist</h2>
  <p class="mag90-intro">Your first three months in Canada set the foundation for your financial future. This <strong>newcomer checklist for Canada</strong> breaks the first 90 days into clear, week-by-week and month-by-month priorities &mdash; from getting your SIN and opening a bank account to building credit, understanding provincial healthcare, and filing your first taxes. Follow this <strong>new immigrant checklist for Canada</strong> in order and you will avoid the most common settlement mistakes.</p>
  <div class="mag90-timeline">
    <div class="mag90-card"><span class="mag90-tag">Week 1 &middot; Arrival</span><h3>Get the Essentials in Place</h3><ul class="mag90-list"><li><strong>Apply for your SIN</strong> (Social Insurance Number) &mdash; free and required to work or open most accounts.</li><li><strong>Open a newcomer bank account</strong> with no monthly fee for the first year.</li><li><strong>Get a Canadian phone number</strong> and an affordable prepaid or postpaid plan.</li><li><strong>Set up online and mobile banking</strong> so you can pay bills and track spending.</li></ul></div>
    <div class="mag90-card"><span class="mag90-tag">Month 1 &middot; Settle</span><h3>Find Your Footing</h3><ul class="mag90-list"><li><strong>Find housing</strong> &mdash; secure short-term then long-term rental accommodation.</li><li><strong>Apply for provincial healthcare</strong> and learn your province's waiting period.</li><li><strong>Create a realistic monthly budget</strong> based on Canadian living costs.</li><li><strong>Register for key services</strong> &mdash; utilities, internet, and transit.</li></ul></div>
    <div class="mag90-card"><span class="mag90-tag">Month 2 &middot; Build</span><h3>Grow Your Stability</h3><ul class="mag90-list"><li><strong>Start building credit</strong> with a secured or newcomer credit card.</li><li><strong>Explore employment opportunities</strong> and have your credentials assessed.</li><li><strong>Register for local services</strong> &mdash; library, settlement agency, language classes.</li><li><strong>Set up automatic bill payments</strong> to protect your new credit history.</li></ul></div>
    <div class="mag90-card"><span class="mag90-tag">Month 3 &middot; Plan</span><h3>Secure Your Future</h3><ul class="mag90-list"><li><strong>Understand the Canadian tax system</strong> and your filing obligations.</li><li><strong>Build an emergency fund</strong> covering three to six months of expenses.</li><li><strong>Establish a long-term financial plan</strong> with TFSA and RRSP basics.</li><li><strong>Review your credit report</strong> from Equifax and TransUnion for accuracy.</li></ul></div>
  </div>
  <div class="mag90-callout">
    <div class="mag90-box mag90-tips"><h4>Practical Tips</h4><ul><li>Open your account through a bank's <a href="https://moneyabroadguide.com/best-banks-newcomers-canada-2026/">newcomer program</a> to waive fees and unlock a no-credit-history credit card.</li><li>Keep digital and paper copies of your passport, permit, and proof of address &mdash; you will need them repeatedly.</li><li>Ask your settlement agency about free, government-funded newcomer services in your area.</li><li>Start your <a href="https://moneyabroadguide.com/canada-budget-planner-2026/">budget</a> in week one, before spending patterns set in.</li></ul></div>
    <div class="mag90-box mag90-mistakes"><h4>Common Mistakes to Avoid</h4><ul><li>Waiting months to apply for credit &mdash; the sooner you start, the sooner your score grows.</li><li>Missing your province's healthcare waiting period and going uninsured.</li><li>Signing a long lease before understanding the true <a href="https://moneyabroadguide.com/cost-of-living-in-canada-for-new-immigrants-2026-guide/">cost of living</a> in your city.</li><li>Carrying a high credit card balance, which hurts your new credit utilization ratio.</li></ul></div>
  </div>
</section>
