<section class="mageeat" id="about-author" aria-label="About the Author">
 <div class="mageeat-card">
  <span class="mageeat-role">About the Author</span>
  <h2>Talal Eddaouahiri &mdash; Founder of MoneyAbroadGuide</h2>
  <p>Talal Eddaouahiri is the founder of MoneyAbroadGuide.com. A Moroccan immigrant who settled in the United States in 2015, he has worked in retail banking, customer relations, and financial services, and has personally navigated the financial systems of the USA, Canada, Spain, and Morocco.</p>
  <p>He created MoneyAbroadGuide to help newcomers, immigrants, and international students navigate banking, credit building, money transfers, taxes, and personal finance in the USA and Canada.</p>
  <h3>Published Work</h3>
  <div class="mageeat-book"><strong>Author of:</strong> <em>Build Your Credit Score in the USA</em> (2026 Edition) &mdash; a complete, step-by-step guide for newcomers building a strong credit profile from scratch.</div>
 </div>
 <div class="mageeat-card" id="how-we-research">
  <span class="mageeat-role">Editorial Standards</span>
  <h2>How We Research Our Guides</h2>
  <p>Recommending a financial product or strategy to a newcomer is a responsibility we take seriously. Every guide on MoneyAbroadGuide follows a structured research and verification process designed to keep our advice accurate, current, and genuinely useful.</p>
  <div class="mageeat-process">
   <div class="mageeat-step"><h4>Research Process</h4><p>We map each topic against the real questions newcomers ask, then research it from the ground up using primary sources.</p></div>
   <div class="mageeat-step"><h4>Fact Verification</h4><p>Every figure, fee, and requirement is checked against the official source before it is published.</p></div>
   <div class="mageeat-step"><h4>Official Government Sources</h4><p>For SIN, taxes, healthcare, and immigration details we rely on Government of Canada and provincial sources.</p></div>
   <div class="mageeat-step"><h4>Financial Institution Verification</h4><p>Bank fees and newcomer programs are confirmed directly against each institution's published terms.</p></div>
   <div class="mageeat-step"><h4>Annual Updates</h4><p>Guides are reviewed and refreshed at least once a year &mdash; this page reflects 2026 data.</p></div>
   <div class="mageeat-step"><h4>Editorial Independence</h4><p>Our recommendations are never for sale. Affiliate partnerships never influence what we recommend or how we rank it.</p></div>
  </div>
 </div>
</section>"},"elements":[],"widgetType":"html"},{"id":"mag-faq-001","elType":"widget","settings":{"html":"<section class="mag-faq-section" aria-label="Frequently Asked Questions">
  <div class="mag-faq-header">
    <h2 class="mag-faq-title">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <p class="mag-faq-subtitle">Answers to the most common questions from newcomers to Canada</p>
  </div>

  <div class="mag-faq-list" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/FAQPage">

    <div class="mag-faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
      <details class="mag-faq-details">
        <summary class="mag-faq-question" itemprop="name">
          <span>How can I open a bank account in Canada as a newcomer with no credit history?</span>
          <span class="mag-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="mag-faq-answer" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
          <div itemprop="text">
            <p>Most major Canadian banks — including RBC, TD, Scotiabank, BMO, CIBC and National Bank — offer dedicated <strong>newcomer banking packages</strong> that require no Canadian credit history. You typically need: a valid passport or government-issued ID, proof of arrival date (e.g. study or work permit, PR card), and a Canadian address. Many banks also allow you to open an account <strong>before you arrive in Canada</strong> through their international banking programs. Digital banks like <strong>Simplii Financial</strong> and <strong>Tangerine</strong> offer free chequing accounts with no monthly fees, making them excellent starting points for newcomers.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>

    <div class="mag-faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
      <details class="mag-faq-details">
        <summary class="mag-faq-question" itemprop="name">
          <span>How do I build a credit score in Canada from scratch?</span>
          <span class="mag-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="mag-faq-answer" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
          <div itemprop="text">
            <p>Building credit in Canada starts with getting a <strong>secured credit card</strong> — where you deposit a fixed amount as collateral. Options include the <strong>Home Trust Secured Visa</strong> and secured cards from major banks. You can also build credit by becoming an authorized user on a family member's card, or by applying for a <strong>credit-builder loan</strong> through a credit union. Key rules: always pay your balance in full before the due date, keep your utilization below 30%, and never miss a payment. Most newcomers see their first credit score appear within <strong>3–6 months</strong> of opening their first credit product.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>

    <div class="mag-faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
      <details class="mag-faq-details">
        <summary class="mag-faq-question" itemprop="name">
          <span>How can I rent an apartment in Canada without Canadian credit history?</span>
          <span class="mag-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="mag-faq-answer" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
          <div itemprop="text">
            <p>Many newcomers successfully rent apartments in Canada without local credit by offering: a <strong>larger security deposit</strong> (often 2–3 months rent), <strong>proof of employment or income</strong> (offer letter, bank statements), <strong>international credit references</strong> or a letter from your previous landlord, and <strong>co-signers</strong> if available. Platforms like <strong>Rentals.ca</strong>, <strong>PadMapper</strong>, and <strong>Facebook Marketplace</strong> list landlords open to newcomers. Private landlords are generally more flexible than property management companies. Some landlords also accept a letter from your employer confirming your position and salary as a substitute for a credit check.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>

    <div class="mag-faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
      <details class="mag-faq-details">
        <summary class="mag-faq-question" itemprop="name">
          <span>What is the average cost of living in Canada for a newcomer?</span>
          <span class="mag-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="mag-faq-answer" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
          <div itemprop="text">
            <p>The cost of living in Canada varies significantly by city. As a rough monthly estimate for a single person: <strong>Toronto and Vancouver</strong> are the most expensive, with rent ranging from $1,800–$3,000+ for a 1-bedroom apartment, plus $400–$600 for groceries, $150–$200 for transportation, and $100–$200 for utilities. <strong>Montreal, Calgary, and Ottawa</strong> are more affordable, with 1-bedroom apartments averaging $1,200–$2,000. Budget cities like <strong>Halifax, Winnipeg, and Edmonton</strong> offer lower costs, with rent from $900–$1,500. Total monthly budget for a comfortable single-person lifestyle ranges from <strong>$2,500 in smaller cities to $4,500+ in Toronto or Vancouver</strong>.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>

    <div class="mag-faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question">
      <details class="mag-faq-details">
        <summary class="mag-faq-question" itemprop="name">
          <span>What are the best high-yield savings accounts for newcomers in Canada?</span>
          <span class="mag-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="mag-faq-answer" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer">
          <div itemprop="text">
            <p>The best high-yield savings options for newcomers in Canada include: <strong>EQ Bank Savings Plus Account</strong> (consistently one of the highest rates, no monthly fees, fully digital), <strong>Simplii Financial High Interest Savings Account</strong> (free and easy to open online), and <strong>Tangerine Savings Account</strong> (often offers promotional rates for new customers). Credit unions like <strong>Meridian</strong> and <strong>Desjardins</strong> also offer competitive rates. For newcomers who want to maximize savings, a <strong>TFSA (Tax-Free Savings Account)</strong> allows you to earn interest tax-free once you are a Canadian resident — this is one of the most powerful savings tools available in Canada.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </details>
    </div><div class="mag-faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question"><details class="mag-faq-details"><summary class="mag-faq-question" itemprop="name"><span>Can I open a Canadian bank account without a SIN?</span><span class="mag-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span></summary><div class="mag-faq-answer" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer"><div itemprop="text"><p>Yes. You can open most Canadian bank accounts without a Social Insurance Number. A SIN is only legally required for accounts that earn interest reported to the CRA, but banks can open a chequing account or a newcomer package using just your passport, immigration document, and proof of a Canadian address. Many of the big five banks &mdash; RBC, TD, Scotiabank, BMO, and CIBC &mdash; let newcomers open accounts before or shortly after arrival without a SIN. You will usually be asked to provide your SIN later once you receive it, especially for savings accounts. If a branch insists a SIN is mandatory to open a basic account, you are within your rights to ask for the no-SIN option, which Canadian banking rules allow.</p></div></div></details></div><div class="mag-faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question"><details class="mag-faq-details"><summary class="mag-faq-question" itemprop="name"><span>What is the best bank for newcomers to Canada?</span><span class="mag-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span></summary><div class="mag-faq-answer" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer"><div itemprop="text"><p>There is no single best bank for every newcomer &mdash; the right choice depends on your priorities. All five major banks (RBC, TD, Scotiabank, BMO, CIBC) offer strong newcomer packages with no monthly fees for up to a year and a credit card with no Canadian credit history required. RBC and Scotiabank's StartRight program are popular for their broad branch networks and bundled offers. TD is known for long branch hours, while BMO and CIBC frequently run cash bonuses. Compare the fee-free period, whether a credit card is included, free international transfers, and branch access near you. Our full Best Banks for Newcomers guide breaks down each program side by side so you can match one to your situation.</p></div></div></details></div><div class="mag-faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question"><details class="mag-faq-details"><summary class="mag-faq-question" itemprop="name"><span>How do newcomers build credit in Canada?</span><span class="mag-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span></summary><div class="mag-faq-answer" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer"><div itemprop="text"><p>Newcomers build credit in Canada by opening credit accounts that report to the two credit bureaus, Equifax and TransUnion, and managing them well. The fastest starting point is a secured or newcomer credit card, which most major banks offer without requiring existing credit history. Use the card for small, regular purchases and pay the balance in full and on time every month. Keep your credit utilization &mdash; the percentage of your limit you use &mdash; below thirty percent. Over time, adding a second credit product and never missing a payment steadily raises your score. Avoid applying for many products at once, as each application can cause a small temporary dip. Consistency over six to twelve months is what builds a solid Canadian credit profile.</p></div></div></details></div><div class="mag-faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question"><details class="mag-faq-details"><summary class="mag-faq-question" itemprop="name"><span>How much money should I bring to Canada?</span><span class="mag-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span></summary><div class="mag-faq-answer" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer"><div itemprop="text"><p>The amount depends on your immigration category and city, but a common guideline is to bring enough to cover three to six months of living expenses while you settle. For a single newcomer in a major city like Toronto or Vancouver, that often means several thousand dollars to cover rent deposits, first and last month's rent, food, transit, phone, and unexpected costs. Express Entry applicants must also meet proof-of-funds requirements set by the Government of Canada, which scale with family size. Beyond the minimum, having a cushion reduces pressure while you find work and wait out any healthcare waiting period. Keep funds accessible, and consider a low-cost international transfer service to move money without losing value to poor exchange rates.</p></div></div></details></div><div class="mag-faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question"><details class="mag-faq-details"><summary class="mag-faq-question" itemprop="name"><span>How does provincial healthcare work in Canada?</span><span class="mag-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span></summary><div class="mag-faq-answer" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer"><div itemprop="text"><p>Healthcare in Canada is publicly funded but administered separately by each province and territory, so coverage and waiting periods vary by where you live. After arriving, you apply for your provincial health card &mdash; for example OHIP in Ontario, MSP in British Columbia, or RAMQ in Quebec. Some provinces provide coverage immediately, while others impose a waiting period of up to three months for new residents. During any waiting period, private interim health insurance is strongly recommended to avoid large medical bills. Public coverage generally includes doctor visits and hospital care but often excludes prescription drugs, dental, and vision, which many residents cover through employer benefits or private insurance. Apply for your health card as early as possible after you arrive.</p></div></div></details></div><div class="mag-faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question"><details class="mag-faq-details"><summary class="mag-faq-question" itemprop="name"><span>Can I rent an apartment without credit history in Canada?</span><span class="mag-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span></summary><div class="mag-faq-answer" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer"><div itemprop="text"><p>Yes, newcomers regularly rent apartments without Canadian credit history, though you may need to reassure landlords in other ways. Common approaches include offering a larger deposit or several months of rent upfront, providing proof of employment or an offer letter, showing bank statements or proof of funds, and supplying references from previous landlords abroad. A guarantor or co-signer with Canadian credit can also strengthen your application. Renting from individual landlords or smaller buildings is often easier than large corporate property managers that rely heavily on automated credit checks. Being organized with a complete application package &mdash; ID, proof of income, references, and a polite cover note &mdash; goes a long way. Our Rent Without Credit guide covers landlord-approved strategies in detail.</p></div></div></details></div><div class="mag-faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question"><details class="mag-faq-details"><summary class="mag-faq-question" itemprop="name"><span>What taxes do new immigrants pay in Canada?</span><span class="mag-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span></summary><div class="mag-faq-answer" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer"><div itemprop="text"><p>Once you become a resident of Canada for tax purposes, you generally pay tax on your worldwide income, including employment income, investment income, and certain foreign earnings. Canada uses a progressive system with both federal and provincial income tax, deducted automatically from most paycheques. You will also encounter sales taxes (GST, HST, or PST depending on the province) on many goods and services. Your residency start date matters, and your first tax return is often partial for the year you arrive. Filing a return &mdash; even with little or no income &mdash; is important because it can unlock benefits and credits such as the GST/HST credit and the Canada Child Benefit. When in doubt, consult the CRA or a tax professional for your first filing.</p></div></div></details></div><div class="mag-faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question"><details class="mag-faq-details"><summary class="mag-faq-question" itemprop="name"><span>How long does it take to build a credit score in Canada?</span><span class="mag-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span></summary><div class="mag-faq-answer" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer"><div itemprop="text"><p>You typically need at least three to six months of active credit activity before a meaningful credit score appears, and around twelve months of consistent, responsible use to reach a solid score. Credit scores in Canada range roughly from 300 to 900. After opening your first credit card and using it responsibly, a basic score usually generates within the first few months. Reaching the 'good' range (around 660 and above) generally takes six to twelve months of on-time payments and low balances. Climbing into the 'very good' or 'excellent' range takes longer and rewards a longer track record, a mix of credit types, and zero missed payments. Patience and consistency matter far more than any quick trick.</p></div></div></details></div><div class="mag-faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question"><details class="mag-faq-details"><summary class="mag-faq-question" itemprop="name"><span>What is a newcomer banking package?</span><span class="mag-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span></summary><div class="mag-faq-answer" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer"><div itemprop="text"><p>A newcomer banking package is a special bundle that Canadian banks offer to people who recently immigrated. These packages are designed to remove the usual barriers newcomers face. Typical perks include no monthly account fees for the first year or longer, a credit card approved without Canadian credit history, free or discounted international money transfers, and sometimes a cash welcome bonus or a free safety deposit box. To qualify, you usually need to have arrived in Canada within a set window (often the last few years) and provide your passport and immigration documents. Each major bank brands its package differently &mdash; such as Scotiabank's StartRight or BMO's NewStart &mdash; but the core benefits are similar. They are one of the easiest ways to start banking and building credit at once.</p></div></div></details></div><div class="mag-faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question"><details class="mag-faq-details"><summary class="mag-faq-question" itemprop="name"><span>Do I need a credit card immediately as a newcomer?</span><span class="mag-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span></summary><div class="mag-faq-answer" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer"><div itemprop="text"><p>Getting a credit card early is one of the smartest first moves, because it is the simplest way to start building Canadian credit history. You do not need it for daily survival, but the sooner you open one and use it responsibly, the sooner your credit score develops &mdash; and credit is required for renting, financing a car, and eventually getting a mortgage. Most newcomer banking packages include a credit card with no Canadian credit history needed, so you can usually get one within your first week. If you are declined for a standard card, a secured credit card &mdash; where you place a refundable deposit &mdash; is an excellent starting tool. Use it for small purchases and pay it off in full each month.</p></div></div></details></div><div class="mag-faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question"><details class="mag-faq-details"><summary class="mag-faq-question" itemprop="name"><span>What documents do I need to settle in Canada?</span><span class="mag-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span></summary><div class="mag-faq-answer" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer"><div itemprop="text"><p>Keep your key documents organized and accessible, as you will use them repeatedly during your first weeks. Essentials include your valid passport, your immigration document (permanent resident card, work permit, or study permit), and proof of your Canadian address such as a lease or utility bill. You will also need these to apply for your SIN, open a bank account, get a health card, and sign a rental lease. Bring originals plus several photocopies and digital scans stored securely. Other useful documents include your birth certificate, marriage certificate, educational credentials and transcripts (often needed for credential assessment), driving records from your home country, and any vaccination or medical records. Having everything ready prevents delays when applying for services.</p></div></div></details></div><div class="mag-faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question"><details class="mag-faq-details"><summary class="mag-faq-question" itemprop="name"><span>How do I get a SIN in Canada?</span><span class="mag-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span></summary><div class="mag-faq-answer" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer"><div itemprop="text"><p>A Social Insurance Number is free and required to work in Canada or access government programs. You can apply online through Service Canada, by mail, or in person at a Service Canada Centre. You will need your primary identity document &mdash; such as your permanent resident card, work permit, or study permit &mdash; and your passport. In-person applications are often processed on the spot, while online and mail applications take a little longer. There is never a fee to get a SIN, so avoid any service that charges for it. Once issued, treat your SIN like sensitive personal information: share it only when legally required, such as with employers, banks for interest-bearing accounts, and the CRA, to protect yourself against identity theft.</p></div></div></details></div><div class="mag-faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question"><details class="mag-faq-details"><summary class="mag-faq-question" itemprop="name"><span>When can I apply for permanent residency or citizenship?</span><span class="mag-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span></summary><div class="mag-faq-answer" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer"><div itemprop="text"><p>The timing depends on your immigration pathway. Many newcomers arrive already as permanent residents through programs like Express Entry, while others enter on work or study permits and transition to permanent residency later through federal or provincial programs. To apply for Canadian citizenship, you must first be a permanent resident and meet the physical presence requirement &mdash; generally being physically present in Canada for at least 1,095 days within the five years before applying &mdash; along with tax filing and language requirements. Because immigration rules change and individual situations vary, always confirm current eligibility and timelines through the official Government of Canada immigration website or a licensed immigration consultant or lawyer before making decisions.</p></div></div></details></div><div class="mag-faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question"><details class="mag-faq-details"><summary class="mag-faq-question" itemprop="name"><span>What is the difference between a chequing and savings account?</span><span class="mag-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span></summary><div class="mag-faq-answer" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer"><div itemprop="text"><p>A chequing account is your everyday transaction account &mdash; used for receiving your pay, paying bills, making debit purchases, and withdrawing cash. It usually earns little or no interest and is built for frequent activity. A savings account is designed to hold money you do not need right away and pays interest so your balance grows over time, but it may limit how often you can withdraw. As a newcomer, you will typically open a chequing account first for daily life, then add a savings or high-yield savings account to set aside an emergency fund. Keeping the two separate makes budgeting easier and helps you avoid spending money you meant to save. Many newcomer packages let you open both at once.</p></div></div></details></div><div class="mag-faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question"><details class="mag-faq-details"><summary class="mag-faq-question" itemprop="name"><span>Should I keep my bank account in my home country?</span><span class="mag-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span></summary><div class="mag-faq-answer" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer"><div itemprop="text"><p>It often makes sense to keep your home-country account open during your transition, at least temporarily. It can help you manage remaining bills, receive funds, or maintain financial ties while you establish yourself in Canada. However, be mindful of foreign account reporting rules, potential maintenance fees, and the cost of moving money between countries. Using a low-cost international transfer service rather than a traditional bank wire usually saves significantly on fees and exchange rates. Over time, many newcomers consolidate their finances in Canada once their banking, credit, and income are established. If you hold significant foreign assets, ask a Canadian tax professional about any reporting obligations to the CRA so you stay compliant.</p></div></div></details></div><div class="mag-faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question"><details class="mag-faq-details"><summary class="mag-faq-question" itemprop="name"><span>How do I transfer money to and from Canada cheaply?</span><span class="mag-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span></summary><div class="mag-faq-answer" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer"><div itemprop="text"><p>Traditional bank wire transfers are convenient but often carry high fees and unfavourable exchange rates. Dedicated money transfer services typically offer far better value. Providers like Wise are known for using the mid-market exchange rate with low, transparent fees, while Remitly is popular for family remittances, and OFX and Xe work well for larger one-off transfers. To save the most, always compare the total cost &mdash; not just the advertised fee, but the exchange rate margin too &mdash; and check the delivery speed that matches your need. For recurring transfers, some services let you lock in rates or set up automatic transfers. Our guide to the best money transfer apps from Canada compares these options in detail.</p></div></div></details></div><div class="mag-faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question"><details class="mag-faq-details"><summary class="mag-faq-question" itemprop="name"><span>What is a TFSA and an RRSP?</span><span class="mag-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span></summary><div class="mag-faq-answer" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer"><div itemprop="text"><p>The Tax-Free Savings Account (TFSA) and Registered Retirement Savings Plan (RRSP) are two of Canada's main tax-advantaged accounts. A TFSA lets your investments grow and be withdrawn completely tax-free, making it flexible for both short-term and long-term goals; contribution room accumulates each year you are a resident and eligible. An RRSP is built mainly for retirement: contributions are tax-deductible and reduce your taxable income now, while withdrawals are taxed later, ideally when your income is lower. As a newcomer, your TFSA room generally starts the year you become a resident, and your RRSP room is based on your earned income. Both are powerful tools for building long-term wealth, and most newcomers start with a TFSA for its simplicity and flexibility.</p></div></div></details></div><div class="mag-faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question"><details class="mag-faq-details"><summary class="mag-faq-question" itemprop="name"><span>How do I find a job as a newcomer in Canada?</span><span class="mag-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span></summary><div class="mag-faq-answer" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer"><div itemprop="text"><p>Finding work as a newcomer usually combines online job boards, networking, and using free settlement services. Start by tailoring your resume to Canadian standards, which favour a concise, achievement-focused format. Government-funded settlement agencies offer free help with resumes, interview practice, and job-search workshops specifically for newcomers. Networking is especially important in Canada &mdash; informational interviews and professional associations often lead to opportunities that are never advertised. If your profession is regulated, you may need a credential assessment or licensing before working in your field, so research that early. Bridging programs and 'survival jobs' can provide income and Canadian experience while you work toward your target role. Persistence, local references, and Canadian experience all strengthen your applications over time.</p></div></div></details></div><div class="mag-faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question"><details class="mag-faq-details"><summary class="mag-faq-question" itemprop="name"><span>Do I need Canadian work experience to get hired?</span><span class="mag-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span></summary><div class="mag-faq-answer" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer"><div itemprop="text"><p>Many employers value Canadian work experience, and the lack of it is one of the most common frustrations newcomers report &mdash; but it is far from an absolute barrier. You can build local experience through bridging programs, internships, volunteering, contract roles, or entry-level positions in your field. These create Canadian references and demonstrate your ability to work within local norms. Highlighting transferable skills, international achievements, and any Canadian certifications helps offset the gap. Networking and settlement agencies can connect you with employers who actively hire newcomers. Over time, even a short stint of Canadian experience significantly strengthens your applications. Treat your first role as a stepping stone rather than your final destination, and keep building local connections and credentials.</p></div></div></details></div><div class="mag-faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question"><details class="mag-faq-details"><summary class="mag-faq-question" itemprop="name"><span>What is the cost of living in major Canadian cities?</span><span class="mag-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span></summary><div class="mag-faq-answer" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer"><div itemprop="text"><p>Costs vary widely by city. Toronto and Vancouver are the most expensive, driven largely by high rent, while cities like Montreal, Calgary, Edmonton, and Ottawa tend to be more affordable. Rent is usually the single biggest expense, followed by food, transportation, phone and internet, and health-related costs not covered by public insurance. A single newcomer in a major city should budget carefully for the first few months, as deposits and setup costs add up quickly. Creating a realistic monthly budget before you arrive helps you avoid surprises. Our Cost of Living in Canada guide provides current monthly estimates for Toronto, Vancouver, Montreal, and Calgary so you can plan your finances around your chosen city.</p></div></div></details></div><div class="mag-faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question"><details class="mag-faq-details"><summary class="mag-faq-question" itemprop="name"><span>How do I get a Canadian driver's license?</span><span class="mag-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span></summary><div class="mag-faq-answer" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer"><div itemprop="text"><p>The process depends on your province and your existing driving experience. Some provinces have reciprocal agreements with certain countries that let you exchange your foreign licence directly, while others require written and road tests. Generally you start by visiting your provincial licensing authority with your foreign licence, identification, and proof of residency. Many provinces use a graduated licensing system, but experienced drivers from your home country can sometimes get credit for that experience to shorten the process. Bringing an official driving record or abstract from your home country, translated if necessary, can help you skip stages. Apply early, because having a licence affects car insurance rates and may be needed for everyday life and some jobs. Check your specific province's rules.</p></div></div></details></div><div class="mag-faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question"><details class="mag-faq-details"><summary class="mag-faq-question" itemprop="name"><span>How does car insurance work for newcomers in Canada?</span><span class="mag-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span></summary><div class="mag-faq-answer" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer"><div itemprop="text"><p>Car insurance is mandatory in every province if you drive, but the system and cost vary. Some provinces have public auto insurance, while others use private insurers. As a newcomer, your premium can be high at first because insurers may not recognize your foreign driving history, treating you like a new driver. To lower costs, bring a letter or driving record from your previous insurer proving your years of claims-free driving &mdash; many Canadian insurers will give credit for it. Shopping around and comparing multiple quotes is essential, as rates differ significantly between companies. Other factors include your vehicle, where you live, and your coverage level. Over time, a clean Canadian driving record steadily reduces your premiums.</p></div></div></details></div><div class="mag-faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question"><details class="mag-faq-details"><summary class="mag-faq-question" itemprop="name"><span>What phone plan should newcomers get in Canada?</span><span class="mag-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span></summary><div class="mag-faq-answer" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer"><div itemprop="text"><p>When you first arrive, a prepaid SIM gives you an instant Canadian number with no credit check, which is useful for banking, job applications, and rentals. Once you have ID and ideally a bank account, you can switch to a monthly postpaid plan, which usually offers more data for the money. Canada's major carriers have lower-cost subsidiary brands that often provide better value for newcomers. Compare data allowances, coverage in your area, and whether the plan includes calls to your home country if that matters to you. Avoid locking into a long contract before you understand your usage. Our phone plans guide outlines affordable options so you can stay connected without overpaying in your first months.</p></div></div></details></div><div class="mag-faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question"><details class="mag-faq-details"><summary class="mag-faq-question" itemprop="name"><span>Is my foreign education recognized in Canada?</span><span class="mag-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span></summary><div class="mag-faq-answer" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer"><div itemprop="text"><p>It depends on your field. For many jobs, you can have your foreign credentials assessed by a recognized organization to show how they compare to Canadian standards &mdash; this assessment is often useful for employers and immigration. However, regulated professions such as medicine, nursing, engineering, law, and teaching require licensing through a provincial regulatory body, which may involve exams, additional training, or supervised practice. Start the recognition or licensing process as early as possible, since it can take time. Bridging programs help internationally trained professionals meet Canadian requirements while gaining local experience. Even where full licensing is required, related roles can provide income and experience along the way. Research your specific profession's requirements through the relevant regulatory body or a settlement agency.</p></div></div></details></div><div class="mag-faq-item" itemscope itemprop="mainEntity" itemtype="https://schema.org/Question"><details class="mag-faq-details"><summary class="mag-faq-question" itemprop="name"><span>What free settlement services are available to newcomers?</span><span class="mag-faq-icon" aria-hidden="true">+</span></summary><div class="mag-faq-answer" itemscope itemprop="acceptedAnswer" itemtype="https://schema.org/Answer"><div itemprop="text"><p>Canada offers a wide range of free, government-funded settlement services to help newcomers establish themselves. These services, delivered through settlement agencies across the country, include help with job searches and resumes, language training in English or French, information sessions on housing, healthcare, and finances, mentorship and networking programs, and assistance understanding your rights and local systems. Many are available to permanent residents and some other newcomer categories at no cost. Public libraries are another excellent free resource, offering internet access, workshops, and community connections. Taking advantage of these services early can dramatically smooth your transition and connect you with people who understand exactly what you are going through. Search for an authorized settlement agency in your city to get started.</p></div></div></details></div>

